<subSubSection id="92C83BCFD5AE994355A4561CA1B852C5" pageId="0" pageNumber="135" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="57569B4787C24B9EBE2F70094D37ACAF" pageId="0" pageNumber="135">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6ED2FF6A72F1A0146D2CC3C82C3EA87B" pageId="0" pageNumber="135">
The word &quot; 
<emphasis id="69E9836620FD7FFB2425D63389F02791" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="135">brevicornis</emphasis>
&quot; is derived from the Latins words &quot; 
<emphasis id="595314EB75AD5E80136610CDB7F478F7" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="135">brevi</emphasis>
-&quot; and &quot; 
<emphasis id="ECC76AFFBC06FDEA9BB91B8A704FB747" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="135">cornu</emphasis>
&quot;, referring to having the short suprahumeral horns.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D8B73DF0FD14FBC6A6399D015CA318B2" pageId="0" pageNumber="135" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="A1BF8D0118C872E066C4428DF9F76A00" pageId="0" pageNumber="135">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="11FA1A60E0B357ED96FDD2410B8A679F" pageId="0" pageNumber="135">
This species is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="52B47F7FB0A247FAF953B4CC89926648" genus="S." lsidName="S. sinensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="135" rank="species" species="sinensis">
<emphasis id="29C8EA6EE3AB144158E0B0ABF23B2A35" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="135">S. sinensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Yuan, 2002, but differs from the latter in: (1) forewing veins black and apical limbus black (veins yellow to light brown, apical limbus hyaline in 
<taxonomicName id="AFC2CC7A01B06FD1D9EF44F731AB8085" genus="S." lsidName="S. sinensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="135" rank="species" species="sinensis">
<emphasis id="4BE8E40B005E6EE870941556664F6A97" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="135">S. sinensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) (2) suprahumeral horns short, width between suprahumeral horns apices shorter than body length (as long as body length in 
<taxonomicName id="4236716AACDF3BF0553732F0672FAA54" genus="S." lsidName="S. sinensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="135" rank="species" species="sinensis">
<emphasis id="0756B9BAA877E8A5A9DE679FEC84F61D" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="135">S. sinensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); (3) posterior pronotal process nearly straightly (concave medially in 
<taxonomicName id="E5BADA6B92DEC84A81A0F05D9A2E4A26" genus="S." lsidName="S. sinensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="135" rank="species" species="sinensis">
<emphasis id="73A24C0463481E3ED634E612C85AE0AA" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="135">S. sinensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); (4) scutellum longer than wide (wider than long in 
<taxonomicName id="8E470FA420FC02DAC3880CAEBFB052D0" genus="S." lsidName="S. sinensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="135" rank="species" species="sinensis">
<emphasis id="DD736244F2651EFCC4D66908B4CCCAF6" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="135">S. sinensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); (5) apex of posterior pronotal process not reaching M3+4 veins (exceeding M3+4 veins in 
<taxonomicName id="DC1D52B5C6B0B36C66D2F7AB55E2C56F" genus="S." lsidName="S. sinensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="135" rank="species" species="sinensis">
<emphasis id="FD4313DA07EF862EEB28ECF87531D233" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="135">S. sinensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
